{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \C4. With no clear honor sequence to lead from, fourth-best from your longest suit, the clubs, is the standard choice against this heart game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
I am in 4\H. My long suit is the heart holding in dummy, headed by the ace and king and packed with the jack, ten, nine and a string of small cards, sitting opposite my doubleton. That suit is the engine of the hand: I pull trumps and the long hearts simply run, since there are no missing honors to drive out. Counting my five top spades alongside the running hearts there is no real problem here, so my plan is to draw trumps and cash the long suit, keeping an eye on entries to dummy.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \C4, which looks like a fourth-best, so the suit is likely splitting four-one or so around the table; with no club in dummy I can ruff it. From here the principle is clear: lead trumps to draw the opponents' hearts, and because dummy's heart suit has no gaps above my small cards, every round wins once the outstanding trumps fall. The long hearts in dummy account for the bulk of my tricks, my five top spades fill out the rest, and the count reconciles comfortably to the twelve tricks the hand is worth. I just make sure dummy stays reachable so I can enjoy the whole heart suit.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The heart suit was so solid it ran by force the moment the opponents' trumps were gone, and keeping dummy reachable let me cash every one. Reading the club lead and ruffing kept the line clean. Nicely counted and very well played.}
