{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \C3. Without a strong sequence to attack, fourth-best from your longest suit, the clubs, is the textbook lead against four hearts.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
I am in 4\H. Dummy's long heart suit is headed by the ace, queen, jack, ten and nine, opposite my four small ones, and that is where my extra tricks live. The catch is the missing heart king: this suit does not simply run by force, so I will need the king placed favorably and take a finesse through it. My plan is to use the long suit for length, leading toward dummy's honors and finessing for the king, while saving entries so I can repeat the lead if needed.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \C3, which looks like a fourth-best from length rather than a sequence, so I can win my top clubs safely. The heart suit is the source of tricks, but with the king out I must lead toward dummy and finesse: if the king sits with West over dummy's honors the finesse works and the suit yields five tricks. I keep an entry to my hand in reserve in case I need to repeat the heart finesse, then add my top spades and clubs. Played this way the count reconciles to the ten tricks the hand is worth.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
This long suit needed the king onside, so the finesse, not brute force, was the key, and keeping an entry let me lead hearts more than once. Patience with the entries made all the difference. Well judged and smoothly played.}
