{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \D7. With no clear sequence to attack, the top of a doubleton is a safe, passive start that keeps your other holdings intact for later.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
I am in 4\H and need ten tricks. Counting from the top I see the \HA plus a strong trump suit, the \SA \SK \SQ, and the \DA \DK, which gets me into double figures but I want to be sure. My side spades are AKQ3 opposite three small, a five-card suit where a fourth round can be promoted into one more winner by force. The plan is to draw trumps, then play spades enough times that my fourth spade grows into a trick, keeping a trump entry to dummy in reserve.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \D7, which looks like top of a short holding rather than an attack, so I can win the \DA in dummy and get on with the hand. The trumps are headed by KJT94 facing the ace, so only the queen is out; I will lead trumps and lose at most one round, hedging on where that queen sits. Then I turn to spades: AKQ cash, and a fourth round drives out the outstanding J and T, after which my last spade is a winner. With trumps and the \DK as entries between the hands I can return to cash that promoted spade, bringing me to my ten tricks and more.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The key was seeing that the fifth spade was a free trick once the suit was led often enough to clear the missing honours, and saving an entry to reach it. Counting the suit out instead of stopping at the top three is exactly the habit that turns close contracts into comfortable ones. Very nicely done.}
